# {{name}}

A mountly **host shell**: a static page that loads verticals on intent via an import map + `<mountly-feature>` elements.

## Run

```sh
pnpm install
pnpm dev        # serves this folder
```

Open the page and click the widget trigger. The vertical loads from the URL in
`manifest.json`.

## How it works

1. `host.js` calls `bootstrapMountly("./manifest.json")` — fetch manifest → inject
   import map → define `<mountly-feature>` elements, in the right order.
2. `manifest.json` lists shared platform deps (React, mountly) and one entry per
   vertical (team-owned widget published to a CDN).
3. Each `<mountly-feature module-id="...">` mounts its vertical when its `trigger` fires.

## Add a vertical

1. A team scaffolds a widget: `npx mountly init their-widget` and publishes
   `dist/peer.js` to a CDN.
2. Add an entry to `manifest.json` `verticals`:
   ```json
   { "id": "their-widget", "url": "https://cdn.example.com/their-widget@1.0.0/dist/peer.js", "featureExport": "theirWidget" }
   ```
3. Drop `<mountly-feature module-id="their-widget" trigger="click">…</mountly-feature>`
   into the HTML.

## Validate before deploy

```sh
pnpm validate   # mountly manifest validate ./manifest.json
```

Catches duplicate React, version skew, and duplicate vertical ids. Wire it into CI.

## Runtime verticals

To register a vertical fetched after load (e.g. a per-user plugin list), use
`setVertical` from `mountly-manifest`. See the
[micro-frontends guide](https://github.com/jagreehal/mountly/blob/main/docs/micro-frontends.md).
